main event: On December 3, 1957, in Tensleep, Wyoming, two observers reported seeing a round, bright white object, much brighter than the stars, the size of a car, which disappeared after 55 seconds.
interesting points: The object was reported to be without a tail or exhaust trail, and no sound was heard when it disappeared.
It disappeared at a 35-degree angle from the ground, with no halo moon reflection left behind.
The report provides the names of the observers, their ages, and details about the weather conditions during the sighting.
The conclusion of the report was that the object was likely the planet Venus, as indicated by astro computer and charts.
The report suggests that the reliability of the observation was questionable based on the conclusion that the object was a balloon or possibly a balloon.
